\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Difference Approximation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x),$
\end_inset

 find 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{'}(x)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(x)=sin(x)\rightarrow u^{'}(x)=cos(x).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

What if 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is complicated or what if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 is not given analytically? ***insert picutres***
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{+}u(x)=\frac{u(x+h)-u(x)}{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some small parameter.
 Similarly we can define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{-}u(x)=\frac{u(x)-u(x-h)}{h}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Both 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{+}u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{-}u$
\end_inset

 are first order accurate approximations to 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{'}(x),$
\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{h\rightarrow0}|D_{+}u(x)-u^{'}(x)|=\mathcal{O}(h),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 goes down by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 then error goes down by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{0}u=\frac{D_{+}u+D_{-}u}{2}=\frac{u(x+h)-u(x-h)}{2h}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{h\rightarrow0}|D_{0}u(x)-u^{'}(x)|=\mathcal{O}(h^{2}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the error reduction in this case is by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

